{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_ilia_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150849/1930071801/0491.xml":{"full_text":"SOUTH BEND NEWS- TIMES\nDaily Evening-\u2014Sunday\n3. M. STEPHEN80N. publisher\nMORTIMER P. BEEp, General Manager\nMcCBEADT HUSTON. Editor.\nMember: Audit Bureau of Circulation\nr\nFull Leased Wire Sendee\nUnited Preset\u2014International News Service\nUnited News\nPhone: S\u20143121 (Branch Exchange)\nNational Adr. Representative*\nLORENZEN THOMPSON, Inc.\nNew Xork. Chicago, San Francisco. Loa Angelas.\nTERMS OP SUBSCRIPTION\nCarrier Service\u2014\nDally and Sunday, per week.....20 Cents\nPally and Sunday, one year.......910.00\nBy Mail\nPally and Sunday on rural routes, One year...$0.00\nAll others by mall.$7.00\nEntered at 8outh Bend Post Office aa Second- Claas Mall.\nAN INDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER\nOUR PLATFORM\n1. Extend elevation of railrdad tracks.\n2. A plaza facing the Union station.\n3. Build the Washington street bridge.\n4. A boulevard and park system along the\nSt. Joseph river.\n5. Beautify South Bend.\n6. A sewage disposal plant.\no\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nThose who have an opportunity to compare the\nsituation of South Bend with other cities of similar\nsize In the United States, either through travel or\nby reports, find that this city Is much above the\naverage of other communities in business activity.\nOne reflection is the volume of newspaper advertis\ning. Comparative figures on this are readily avail\nable and show that South Bend is holding up re-\nmarkably well In this respect.\nAn authoritative opinion on the subject of South\nN Bend\u2019s general position in business and Industry was\ngiven to the Rotary club* thi! week by Rome C.\nStephenson, who as a high officer of the Ameri\ncan Bankers\u2019 association has Just completed a trip\nfrom coast to coast, addressing and conferring with\nbanking groups. He declares that \u201calthough South\nBend has felt- the depression, the citizens of this\ncommunity should feel that they are, indeed, for\ntunate, as there is not a community in the country\ntoday that is in better financial condition.\u201d\nSpeaking In general about the business outlook, he\nforecast a marked improvement this fall,^ after the\nseasonal slackness of summer is past. \"The last\nquarter of 1930 should show a substantial revival\nin all business lines,\u201d he predicted. Then speaking\nspecifically of South 'Bend, he mentioned some of\nthe favorable signs In industry; prospects that the\nnew Studebaker models may lead to heavy produc\ntion in the near future; the Improved trade position\nof the Bendix corporation; and the fact that the\nOliver Farm Equipment Is enjoying, on the whole, a\ngood year.\nWe do not believe that this forecast is exaggerated\nas it comes from a conservative and Informed source.\nEncouraging business signs are evident to an who\nare not willfully blind.\n4\nTHE MOONEY CASE\nJohn McDonald,. missing witness in the Mooney\ncase, lias '*een found at last; end in that fact lies\na bit of great good luck, not only for Tom Mooney\n1 and Warren K. Billings, but for the nation as a\nwhole. His sudden appearance makes it probable\nthat the case will be definitely cleared up at last.\nSan Francisco held a preparedness parade in 1918.\nA bomb, left in a suitcase at the comer of Stuart\nand Market streets, exploded, killing a number of\npeople.\nMooney and Billings, labor agitators, were arrested\nand charged with the crime. McDonald was the\nstar witness. He swore he had seen Billings leave\nthe suitcase on the corner, join Mooney and talk\nwith him and then walk away. Chiefly on the\nstrength of his testimony, the t~o men were con\nvicted and imprisoned.\nFive years later McDonald appeared in New York\nand swore that he had lied. He had never seen\nMooney and Billings at all, he said; he would not\nhave been able to identify them if the police had\nnot pointed them out to him in jail. He prepared\nto go back and tell his story; but when he learned\nthat he would be prosecuted for perjury he vanished.\nNow he has turned up again, and it is hard to\nsee how Mooney and Billings can be kept in prison\nany longer. F. C. Oxman, the only other important\nwitness against them, has been proved to be a liar.\nThe judge who tried Mooney and nine of the ten\nsurviving jurors who convicted him have asked that\nthe men be freed, saying that they are now. con-\nvinced of their innocence. McDonald\u2019s final appear\nance ought to settle things.\nCalifornia\u2019s supreme court refused to free the two\nmen\u2014offering the perfectly amazing reason that even\nif they weren\u2019t guilty they at least probably knew\nsomething about it, and so ought to stay in prison.\nThat is a perfect sample of the way the whole\ncountry has reacted. It had been demonstrated,\nbefore McDonald\u2019s reappearance, that the case\nagainst Mooney and Billings had utterly collapsed;\nbut we all said, in effect\u2014\u201cWell, they\u2019re bad actors\nanyhow; why worry about them?\u2019\u2019\nBecause of this prejudiced attitude the California\nsupreme court was able to make its absurd remark\n\u2014forgetting, apparently, that Mooney and Billings\nweren\u2019t accused of having knowledge of the bombing,\nor of being bad actors generally, but solely of having\nplanted the bomb.\nIf, at this late date, we are compelled to admit\nthat we have made a terrible mistake; if we are com\npelled to admit that our prejudices have made us\ncommit a tragic injustice; if all of us, from the Cali\nfornia supreme court on down, are compelled to\nrealize that this \u201cwell-anyhow-they-knew-somethlng-\nabout-it\u201d reasoning is utter nonsense\u2014then, as a\nnation, we shall be much better off We shall have\npurged ourselves of something that has been very\nbad for us. We shall have ended a dishonest, wilfully\nblind mental attitude.\nIt is our good luck, as well as Mooney\u2019s and Bil\nlings\u2019s, that McDonald has turned up; and this does\nnot mean that this paper sympathizes with the pris\noners\u2019 radical labor philosophy. That has nothing\nto do with questions of fact and law which are in\nvolved. If Mooney and Billings were unjustly sen\ntenced and the error can now be shown, they should\nbe released; for dangerous radicalism thrives on the\nIdea of martyrdom.\nBACK TO THE TREES\n\u25a0'J- It\u2019s doubtful if these young hopefuls throughout\nthe land whose ambition is to sit in a tree longer\nthan anybody else ever heard of St. Simeon Stylites.\nv>;' Bt Simeon was the original pillar-sitting hermit\nsi back in one of the early centuries of the Christian\ni era. History relates that he was expelled fnua a\nmonastery because he was regarded as one who\ncarried his asceticism to extremes.\nBo he buQt himself a pillar, and lived ob its\nj-'\ntop. At first he added la feet to Its height each\nyew. then when It reached the height of 00 feet\nhe was satisfied and stayed at Its top, with the\nburning sun beating down upon him, for 90 years.\nBe built a little railing around the top of the pillar\nand hla admiring disciples brought food and water\nto him. The story seems well authenticated, being\nvouched for by Theodaret, a historian who knew the\nhermit personally and is regarded as reliable.\nSt. Simeon Stylites had many imitators, includ\ning religious ones down to the 15th century and the\nlatter-day lay sitters, both flagpole and tree. One\nof these imitators, although he may not know it,\nis Jimmy Sugonlts, the lad who at this writing is\nstill perched in a tree on the courthouse lawn, in\ndefiance both' of the laws of nature and the county\ncommissioners. Jimmy, who first simply sat astride\na limb with his foot resting in a looped rope, now\nIs on a little platform and has been sleeping iiw<y\u00bbr\ncovers. The tree is pretty substantial and the boy\u2019s\nwants are being taken care of by a refueling squad.\nThere\u2019s no accounting for what young boys may\ndo. We wonder what Jimmy has been thiwiHwg.\nabout up there. We hope Jimmy\u2019s expectations are\nnot too high for the rewards he may get for his\nfeat, supposing, even, that he does break a record.\nWe hopev the county commissioners do not decide to\ncut down the tree before Jimmy comes down.\nv-\u2014\nJames M. Lynch, who died Wednesday\u2019 in Syra\ncuse, N. Y., was a prominent figure in the Typo\ngraphical union, of which he was a former presi\ndent, and in national labor circles. He was a leader\nin the movement for an eight hour day, now general\nin printing establishments, and was a factor in the\ngrowth of his union, which is regarded as one of\nthe strongest labor organizations in the world.\n-o\nThe governor of Indiana complains that the state\nhouse square is being used for petting parties. Tbo\nbad Attorney General Ogden didn\u2019t hear about it\nfirst. Or Is the governor trying to distract\" public\nattention from his home town of Lafayette?\n\u2014o\nThat was rather a curious statement .by Governor\nYoung of California in which he said that the\nnew evidence in the Mooney case will not be heard\nuntil after the August primary, election.\no\nThis Is the last week to enter the elimination con\ntents for the Chicago music festival Are there any\nmore ambitious vocalists? Sunday is the final day\nto enter.\n-o\nThe next thing, some one will propose a law against\nboys sitting in tree\u2014not because it hurts the tree\nbut because it gives amusement to the specators.\n.o\nFort Wayne makes a bid for summer fame by\nreporting a frost Monday night in lowlands around\nthe city. A July frost is not to be sneezed at.\n-o\nThe state is impatient for the further \u201cstartling\ndevelopments\" promised by Mr. Ogden. Perhaps he\nwill even name the city this time.\ni o\nWith real devotion to their duty the Senators, or\nat least a quorum of them, are staying on In Wash\nington.\n\u2014\u2014o\nThe standpipe will come down, but a new hotel\nIs rising to be the highest structure in the city,\n-o\nOne consolation about this tree-sitting foolish\nness, the mother of the boy knows where he Is.\nIsn\u2019t It about time for Mr. Ogden to make some\nmore remarks about wickedness In Indiana?\n-o-\nConsoling thought for the youngsters: only about\naix weeks mare of summer vacation.\n.--o\u2014_\nSome of these small tree-bound boys are sitting\nstill longer than they ever did before.\n-o\u2014\nAnother contender in the tree-sitting contest is\nthe Republican national chairman.\n\u2014-o\nIf you get sunburned on the bathing beach it surfs\nyou right.\n-o\nThese tree-sitting contests should interest the evo\nlutionists.\n5 w\nWonder if Mr. Coolidge has any anticipations lor 1\n1032.\n-0\nAnyway, a tree is a nice, cool place to sit.\nTODAY\u2019S TALK\nBy GEORGE MATTHEW ADAMS\nLETTERS\nI am a poor correspondent. I dislike to write let\nters. This dislike seems to increase with the years.\nFor why I do not know, unless it be that disillusion\nand disappointment cause one to shrink from that\nsacred expression that should always form the sin\ncere letter.\nLetters, more than any other expression, mirror\nthe mind and heart of the one who writes them.\nNot meant for other eyes than the recipient, there\ncomes to the writer a sincere abandon and freedom\nof outlet than even the most intimate conversation\nnever quite approaches.\nBut I must confess I am one of the \u201call\u201d who\nrejoices in receiving letters from those near and dear,\nor from those to whom there is that something of\ngrace and beauty that enlarges one\u2019s hope and con\nfidence in human relationship.\nFen* days and weeks I carry about with me letters\nthat have come in from all corners of the compass\nletters of appreciation and encouragement from\nthose whom I have never seen, and from whose life\nexperiences have flowed urges and dreams akin to\nmy own. These letters make me feel the pulse beats\nof the world which is partially my own. I can only\nreturn a simple Thank You for these thoughtful\ngifts, but each is happily filed in the Library of\nLetters within my heart, which to me is one of the\nprized possessions of my life!\nLetter's reveal a person. They may not even be\nexpressed in the best of language They may be\nungrammatical and crude. But if they are sincere\nand honest, their worth is immediately established.\nOne of the most touching and pathetic letters I have\never received came from a imu in prison out in\nthe far West. The letter was illiterate and diffi\ncult to read, but something of the hidden divinity\nin man Bowed from its pages.\nYea much as I dislike to write letters, I am always\nhappy in the receipt of one, which in itself is an\nindictment at my dislike to put myself upon paper\nin a letter. Every time I overcome this Printing\ntask, however, and trot the letter upon its way, I\nfeel better and more comfortable inside!\nWouldn\u2019t it be a grand idea to have at least one\nday in the entire year when everybody all over the\nworld would write at least one letter $6 someone?\nXt could be called World Letter Day\n9\u00ae2Kt35(2K7S3\nTHE NEEDIEST CASES FRESH AIR\nFUND\n(Copyright, 193o. by The Associated\nNewspapers.)\nResponse to this department\u2019s Fresh\nAir Fund for Neediest Cases has been\nmost gratifying. President Hoover,\nRear Admiral Byrd and Bobby Jones\nwere given to you as the first three\ncases of persons needing to be taken\naway from it all, the case of Mr. Byrd\nbeing cited as especially urgent. More\nthan $100 has come In, together with\nthe following letters:\nDear Sir:\nYour Fresh Air Fund for persons\nreally needing rest fills a long felt\nneed. The hardships under which\nMr. Hoover has been at Washington\nare well known, and I regard it as ur\ngent that be be sent far away from\nthe Senate, Claudius Huston and the\nFarm Relief Board. I am enclosing\n$1.50 in the hope it will help to take\nMr. Hoover away out into daisy fields\nwhere for at least a whole month he\nwon\u2019t see a Democratic editorial or\neven hear of Hi Johnson. When Mr.\nHoover took the Presidency he was a\nbig, fine, strong and happy man. Now\nlook at him!\nWidow\u2019s Mite.\nI am glad to contribute $2 to the\ncase of Rear Admiral Bird who\nshould be rescued from all those re*\nception and banquet committees at\nonce before it is too late. The way the\ncountry has treated the Admiral since\nhis return has been outrageous. Here\nis a great explorer who risked his life\nin performing one of the greatest\nfeats of all time, and how do we treat\nhim? As if he had swum a channel!\nI understand the poor fellow\u2019s body\nis a mass of medal bruises and that\nhis digestion, due to testimonial din\nners, is all but ruinefi. He must be\nrescued and sent away to a quiet\nplace, far from all reception commit\ntees, bands, motorcycle cops and mic\nrophones at once.\nWhat wouldn\u2019t Rear Admiral Byrd\ngive this minute for a spot where he\ncould get into some old clothes, lie in\nthe hay and not even be reached by\ntelephone or telegram?\nPro Bono Publico.\n\nGentlemen: My little sister and I\nare sending you forty cents, the pro\nceeds of a cake sale, to the fund to\ngive Bobby Jones a vacation. It must\nbe awful to have to go through life\nplaying perfect golf. We hope this\nwill help send him to a place in the\nmountains where the game is never\nmentioned.\nAlice and Jane.\nmm*\nThe fund now stands:\nPreviously acknowledged.$102.35\nA1 Smith ..._.10\nWidow\u2019s Mite 1.50\nPro Bono Publico 2.00\nAlice and Jane .40\nEarl Carroll .50\nCalvin Coolidge .06\n$106.9p\nRHYMES OF A NECKER\nA gal for me\nIs Glenna Snow;\nShe never says,\n\"It\u2019s time to go.\"\nHow I adore\nSusanna Oreer;\nShe never lisps,\n\u201cIt\u2019s too dark here.\u201d\nA man who put three nickles into a\npay station phone without getting' any\nservice smashed the booth and hit a\npoliceman the other day. That\u2019s two\nover par for any phone booth and\nshould entitle the player to burn\ndown the bpilding and take a sock at\na regiment of marines.\n\"Prance Has Surplus of 400,000,000\nGallons of Wine.\u201d\u2014headline. Is there\nno justice?\nOne of the cup defenders, the Wee\ntamoe, was disabled in a light breeze\nrecently. Can\u2019t it be arranged to hold\nthe cup races indoors?\nQueen Mary, it is revealed, smokes\ncigarets. The news that she has bob\nbed her hair and is on her way to the\nbeach in pajamas may come any mo\nment now.\n\u201cAnother Jftdge Off N. Y. Bench.\u201d\u2014\nheadline. It isn\u2019t exactly a bench; it\u2019s\na sort of collapsible chair.\nASTOE\u2019S BIRTH.\nOn July 17, 1864, John Jacob Astor,\nAmerican capitalist, Inventor and\nsoldier, was bom at Rhinebeck, N. Y.\nFollowing his graduation from\nHarvard in 1888, Astor traveled ex\ntensively and afterward devoted his\ntime in the managing of the Astor\nestates. In 1897 he built the Astoria\nhotel, New York, adjoining the Wal\ndorf hotel, which was built by William\nWaldorf Astor, his cousin, the two\nforming one building under the name\nWaldorf-Astoria hotel, at the date of\ncompletion one of the largest and\nmost costly hotels in the world. The\nstructure was -ecently razed to make\nway for a modem skyscraper.\nDuring the Spanish-American war,\nAstor served as staff officer in the\nSantiago campaign and presented to\nthe government a fully equipped\nmountan battery, which was named\nfor him and which did effective work\nin the campaign before Manila.\nAstor became known as an inventor\nof several useful devices, such as the\nbicycle brake and a turbine engine.\nHe was drowned at sea when the Ti\ntanic sank in 1912.\nFRIDAY, JULY 18.\nAn eventful but general hazardous\nstate of affairs is the angury based on\nthis day\u2019s planetary operations. The\ndominant place of Uranus hint of\nsudden change or disruption, with\nnew employment and envionment,\nwhich may not be considered entirely\nwelcome or advantageous. There are\nhazards in these new ventures, and\nwhile personal contacts may bring\nsome satisfaction, yet, even these\nhave their undesirable angles. An all\nround discretion is enjoined.\nThose whose birthday it is are mi\nthe eve of an adventurous year, with\nmuch unforeseen change, and prob\nably travel. Employment and en\nvironment are subject to change, and\npersonal affiliations, although having\nsome beneficial aspects, call for dis\ncretion. Be careful with funds and\nwritings. A child born on this day is\nlikely to have a restless and unsettled\nnature, inciting to frequent change of\nemploment and' environment.\nBELIEVE rr OR NOT\nBy Ripley\nOb ro\u00abaest. sent with stamped, addressed envelope, Mr. Btplejr will fnrnisb proof of anythinc depleted bp him.\nMRS\nJaneftard\nSooth\n-Off Hammond.Ind\npip NOT TAKE A\nPrink of Water\nIK 84 YEARS\nSte lived\ntoo\nWW5\nQkkiefati mfecnokju tnz'k/l&teekJu\nOitJNed by\nUjE H-ALLEN. Erie, 111.\nJUST DIED AT THE ACE\nOP 106 YEARS\n-:---1\nMEANS 31 IN MARQUESAN LANGUAGE\nTHE HEAT\nFROM YOUR\nHANDS WILL\nBOIL A WME\nnptn\nbottle inside Wet 0\ncKme thoroughly and\nplace it an mouth et\nbottle Hold both\nhands around bottle\nand\nVftTCtf\nTHE\nCOIN.\nJ Second-b&sem&n c~*y***\u00a3sk\nwilliam Robinson S~?zsjg*\nia*> 7 chances and made7 errors\nCincinnati\nK June JO.lSi\"\n*930. Kln\u00a3 Features SjrtHfleau, fne\u00ab GfW BritaSn riftt* wrv*L\nOr. Dean will answer all signed letters pertaining to parents' problems\nwith their boys and girls. Writers* names are never printed. Only ques\ntions of general interest answered In this column, but all letters will be\nanswered by mail If written In Ink, and a stamped, self-addressed en\nvelope 1% enclosed. Address Arthur Dean. In care of this paper.\nFather and Son.\nA dad sends me the following letter he received on Father\u2019s Day from his\n19-year-old son, who is now working a thousand miles away from home,\nwith the request that I answer it for him. Here\u2019s the boy\u2019s letter:\n\u201cDear Dad,\n\u201cWell, Dad, How\u2019s everything? Seeing that next Sunday is Dad\u2019s Day, I\ncouldn\u2019t do any better than to write you a letter. May you have all nossible\nJoy and happiness! Thegnore I think of you, Dad, the\nmore I Appreciate everythin* you have done for me. I\nhaven\u2019t said much about it, perhaps I haven\u2019t said\nenough to you, but I want you to know I really like you.\n\u201cThere\u2019s one thing I want to ask you, Dad, right from\nthe shoulderN Where I am working half the men pull\ndirty jokes and talk, sex. my is it they always talk\nthat way? I believe I know less about sex than any\nboy of my age, but if there is no great need of knowing\nmore about it I would Just as soon be ignorant. Can a\nfellow be clean and stay clean and not have any\nknowledge about sex?\n1 am going wun a giri out mere arm l-juii*. u/u\nher. The men in the shop tell of their experiences with girls, but I don\u2019t\nhave such experiences. My girl is clean and straight. But you know, Dad,\nI am' awfully bashful and feel sort of backward with the girls. What\u2019s\nwrong with me?\n\u201cNow I am not going to get married, don\u2019t worry. But I think I am old\nenough to go with girls and I pray ever night that when I need to know\nabout sex that it will be time enough for me to read up on it.\n\u201cSomehow, Dad, this isn\u2019t a very satisfactory letter but it has taken me\ntwo hours to write it. Do you think my vlew\u00a7 are right.\n\"Happy Dad\u2019s Day to you.\n\u201cvnrip rom\nMy Reply.\nDear Son:\nAwfully glad that you like me. I tried to do a good Job in bringing you\nup and in one respect at least I succeeded, namely, I have your confidence.\nYou are a good boy, clean minded, and ambitious. You are to be trusted\naway from home, and are going to amount to something.\nBut somehow your letter cut me deeply. It seems as though in some re\nspects I have failed. You should not be self-conscious and bashful in the\npresence of girls. Your mother and I ought to have encouraged ydu to have\nknown girls so you would be more at ease with them than you are now.\nSome fathers would be proud of the fact that you appear to be so innocent.\nPerhaps I have been proud too, but now after reading your letter I feel\nhumiliated.\nIf you had said, \u201cSome day I am going to Europe but I won\u2019t know any\nthing about Europe, how to get there, what to see when I get there, or what\nis the expense of the trip; but what\u2019s the use of knowing anything about it\nuntil I get there,\u201d I should have thought you were a very foolish boy making\na very foolish statement.\nNow isn\u2019t this just about what you have implied with reference to marriage\nand girls. You are not going to know anything about it until you get there.\nI am sorry that your business associates are not wholesome., A clean mind j\nunder good control is a splendid asset for a young man and your friends\nare \u2122niring a mistake in confining their conversation to the physicaj aspects\nof life.\nI want you to talk about girls and some day about a particular girl; I want\nyou to see her charm, tact, poise, cheerfulness and unselfishness. I want\nyou to see .things in her which will keep your present respect for girls and\nwhich will increase your own self-control.\nSon, you must keep your mind clean by feeding it with fine people, and\nstrict attention to business. But you must also possess technical information\nrelative to some very important functions of life\nI was too much of a coward, or too ignorant, or too foolish, not to have\ngiven you some of these facts when you were younger. If you were not a\nthousand miles away we would sit down together on Father\u2019s Day and go\nover them. But you are miles from my voice even though you are not miles\nfrom my heart. So the next best thing I can do Is to. send you a book. It is\nonly a 10-cent book but tells you the things I ought to have told you. I don\u2019t\nbelieve in handing a book to a boy, it\u2019s so much better to read a sex book to\ngether. It would be a lot better for me to tell you something about my\nown life than to let you be the only one telling me about your life. But, as\nI said before, we are a thousand miles away so I must send the book. May\nit help you. DAD WHO MEANT WELL.\nWalt Mason, Himself\nThe World\u2019s Most Famous Rhymster\nFORBIDDEN THINGS\nWe for forbidden things the gods will not provide us, we can\u2019t\nbe happy as three kings while such things are denied us. When I was\nvourut I hated prunes, they used to gridve and bore me; and wearily I plied\nmy spoons wnen tney were set Deiore me. 1 o:ten voicea\nmy keen distress, in language chaste and polished, and\nurged, in pulpit and in press, that prunes should be\nabolished. But everywhere I chanced to go they fed\nme prunes in dishes, regardless of my rising woe. re*\ngardless of my wishes. They fed me primes in such\ndisguise as well might fool a wizard, they gave me\nprunes in cakes and pies, and so upset my gizzard. Then\nI fell ill upon a day, by dread diseases ridden; and I\n'could hear the doctor say, \u201cStewed prunes must be for\nbidden.\u201d And ever since that afternoon I have been\nlonging, yearning; I\u2019d give my birthright for the prune\nthat once you saw me spuming. And when at night I\ngo to bed, op downy sheets reclining, I dream that I am\nbeing fed stewed prunes by angels shining. A lot of\nmen are sipping rye in joints securely hidden, vile boose\nthat has a\u2018kick like lye, because the stuff\u2019s forbidden.\nThey do sot life the ghastly taste, offensive to all critters, they know it is a\nsinful waste of coin to buy such bitters; but they\u2019re informed they mustn't\ndrink, and so they breathe defiance, and call for stoups of crimson ink pro\nnounced a crime by science. Alas, it is the way we\u2019re built; you warn us of\na danger, and we go far it, plaid and kilt, and prudence is a stranger.\nBELIEVE IT OR NOT\nANSWERS\n\u201cOWNEY,\u201d THE DOG THAT\nTRAVELED AROUND THE\nWORLD ALONE.\nThis remarkable dog has been\npreserved as an exhibit in the\nSmithsonian institute, and was\nalso on exhibit at the Sesqui-Cen\ntennial in Philadelphia in 1927, as\nthe first and only dog to travel\naround the world alone. Owney\nattached himself to the postoffice\nrailway mail service in the early\neighties of last century, and was\nconsidered as a mascot on any\ntrain he selected to have the honor\nof his company. Reference: \u201cNa\nture Magazine\u201d of January, 1927.\nTomorrow\u2014The Tallest One-Story\nHome.\n^TBEDIERKKLAKIDIS\nWhen the Indiana State Bar asso\nciation refused to endorse the pro\nposal to give the Supreme and Appel\nlate courts authority to simplify the\nrules of procedure and pleading it\nadopted the attitude at that Vander\nbilt who said: \u201cThe public be\ndamned!\u201d\nIt is fortunate however the Issue\nwas raised, for now the people know\nwhere to place the blame for the hor\nrible failure of our courts.\nThus we have blandly presented\nthe proposition that courts are not\ntemples of justice, but establishments\nfor the enrichment of the bar, while\nthe constitutional guarantee of speedy\njustice is but an entry in the joke\nbook of the barrister.\nThe rights of men, women and\nchildren are nothing; the safety of\nsociety from crime Is nothing; the\nfees of those who practice laws are\neverything.\nThe Goddess of Justice is not the\nshield of the weak, but a cabaret\ndancer, dedicated to the Joy of \u201cthe\nprofession.\u201d\nFor centuries lawyers have been a\nprivileged class; in their mysterious\nrealm they have dallied with human\nrights as witch doctors have trafflced\nin ignorance and superstition; they\nhave set up and maintained to the\ndetriment of the race an occult code.\nIn all other lines we have pro\ngressed, but the tardy processes of the\nlaw are what they were ages ago;\nwhile all others have climbed the\nladder of improvement, the lawyer\nstill sits in the dim and musty cellar\nof antiquity, holding sweet com\nmunion with the bats of fiction and\ntechnicality.\nCitizens may Suffer because courts\nare congested with law suits; they\nmay tremble because organized crime\nshakes its fist at the state, but the\nIndiana State Bar association is\ntroubled only by the phantom of an\nempty purse.\nThe refusal of this association to\ntake its stand for human welfare is\nas if the State Medical association\nshould refuse to adopt measures to\noppose the ravages of cancer and\ntuberculosis on the ground that the\nremoval of those scourges would re\nduce the revenues of doctors.\nThe Indiana Bar association does\nnot speak for the high minded law\nyers of this state, for they know that\nthe late Chief Justice Taft spoke\nthe truth when he said: \u201cOur admin\nistration of criminal law is a disgrace\nto civilization!\u201d\nAnd they know also that our ad\ni ministration of civil law- is just as\nbad.\nHowever our Supreme and Appellate\ncourts can and should proceed to\nsimplify the rules of procedure and\npleading; they can do almost all tha,t\nis needed without legislative action\nand it is the prayer of a long suffer\ning public that the vaudeville in our\ncourt houses shall end and the reign\nof justice begin.\nRADIO BIRTH.\nLIVERPOOL. Complete medical\ninstructions were wirelessed to the\nsteamer Nacoya at sea when a baby\nwas bom to the captain\u2019s wife.\nCAHST^BCKLrKfir,\nvj edoApl guest\nUNPRAISED MERIT.\nAn eager lad worked side by side\nWith one Vho took in work no pride.\nAnd since they labored by the day\nAnd drew each week the self-same\n_ pay.\nThe youngster, missing words\npraise,\nWondered if honest effort pays.\nOf\nHe noticed, being bright of eye,\nHis careless brother's task go by.\nYet what seemed strange, he never\nbeard\nA bitter or complaining word\nAnd wondered! \u2018\u2018Can it be the same?\nI get so praise; he gets no blame.\n\"Is merit worth its patient cost?\nIs tedious, honest effort lostf\nI give my best; he doesn\u2019t try,\nYet gets the same reward as I.\"\nAnd so one night the eager lad\nDiscussed the question with his dad.\n\"My boy,\" said he, \u201cnor praise nor\nblame\nOf good and bad can make the same.\nIn self-respect high effort pays,\nGood work without one word of praise\nIs better Nhan performance faint\nWhich may be passed without com*\nplaint\"\n(Copyright 1930, Edgar A. Guest)\nPARIS.\u2014I always say au revoir to\nParis with a gulp despite that in\nthese post-helium days the city has\ntaken on the qualities of a beautiful\nbut urttcaceous plant\u2014nettled with\nstinging thorns. The Paris of ex\nquisite gallantry and gushing hos\npitality\u2014so far as Americans are con\ncerned\u2014has almost vanished.\nI speak of Paris alone and not\nPrance as a nation. In the provinces\nthe simple and obliging charm that\ncharacterize the French is unchanged.\nLargely, and in justice to Paris, it is\nour own fault. We have been suckers\nand are paying the price and reaping\nthe whirlwind the sucker sows wher\never he goes.\nThe duality of prices, aimed almost\nsolely at Americans, for the British\nwill not stand thd gaff, in the big\ndressmaking establishments as -well\nas almost every other shop in the city,\noffers #ie most Impertinent hi-jack\ning ever devised. Coupled with this\nis the thieving concierge system in\nAmerican patronized hotels.\nWe who are visiting firemen are not\nso dull we are not perfectly conscious\nFrance has its majority who assay\nhigh in Integrity and culture. But\nmost of us have reached a point\nwhere we would like to meet some of\nthem instead of the rapacious rascals\nthat tradesmen and hotel keepers\nfling in our teeth.\nMultiply this personal incident of\nthe morning by A full score daily and\nyou have a fair idea. A suit of\nclothes was to be delivered to my\nhotel room. At 20 minute intervals\nthree door-pounding ruffians\u2014one\nwith vest, another with coat and still\nanother with pantaloons\u2014upset the\nhousehold, merely to get three tips in\nstead of one.\nIf this trifling Incident were not a\npart of the studied organized petty\nbanditry it would not be mentioned\nhere. But it is. No Frenchman would\nsuffer it, and the most hopeful sign\nthat Americans are not going to\nsuffer it much longer is that Paris\nshops have not been so idle or hotels\nso desolated in many years.\nParis, of all the continental cities,\nis almost wholly dependent upon\ntourists for its financial well being.\nFrance os a whole can get along\nwithout us, but Paris cannot. A\nsecond-rate hotel in Paris now has a\ntariff as high as a first-class hotel in\nNew York, without half the appoint\nments or conveniences. And so it\ngoes.\n\u2014OO\u2014\nIn the days of the tempestuous\nBennett, the Paris Herald was wont\nto tweak the French for any slight\ntoward American visitors. But today\nit seems to me to have become a\ntoadying organ of the Franco-phile.\na ballyhoo for the tea-drinking am\nbassadorial set and a hand-bill for\nthe decadent expatriates who disport\nat the Sunday night dinner dances\nat the Ritz\n\u2014OO\u2014\nAnother thing\u2014I\u2019m pretty mad to\nday\u2014I\u2019m fed up reading in the con\ntinental press about the left Dolly\nsister, or maybe it is the one on the\nright. Anyway it is the one who is\nalways headlined as having a \u201cwin\nning streak\" at the gaming tables of\nLe Touquet or Monte Carlo. At best\nthe Dolly sisters are a pair of medi\nocre and outmoded dancers out of\nthe New York Ghetto, and are no\nmore representative of American\nwomanhood abroad than the palm\nitching servants of Paris are repre\nsentative of the good people of\nFrance.\nI know a cultured man and his\nequally cultured wife who have saved\nfor 15 years to spend a year studying\nthe artistic beauty and architectural\ntriumphs of France. They live fru\ngally in a skylit flat of an old pension\nalong the quay. Each morning they\nattend the free classes of the Sorbon\nne, and in five months speak the\nlanguage without a trace of accent.\nAt the end of the year their finances\nwill be exhausted and they are goim\nback to a little Louisiana town to be\ngin all over again. Each is past 5<\nThat interests me more someho\".\nthan the over-publicized Dolly sister\ncracking the bank at Monte Carle\nBut such stories are never printe.\nover here.\n\u2014OO\nThe Parisian blood fares forth 01\nthe leafy boulevards with a new sar\ntorial conceit these days. His shirt\ncollar, handkerchief and bow tie arc\nof the same material. His clothinj\nmaterial is of vertical striped pattern\nand his lapel flower is a huge red or\nwhite rose. The hat is pulled wel\ndown on the head but not at ar\nangle. His shoes are very pointed\npatent leather with cloth uppers.\n\u2014OO\u2014\nIt is quite childish, 2 suppose, to\nleave Paris in a pout, for of all cities\nover here I loVe and admire it most.\nYet it seems to me something should\nbe done to save it from itself. I sun\nfully determined that I am never\ncoming to Paris again\u2014that is to\nsay; not again this summer.\n(Copyright, 1930, by the McNaught\nSyndicate, Inc.)\nAIM\nThou shalt have no other Gods be\nfore me.\u2014Exodus 20:3.\nm 1\nGod is the only sure foundation on I\nwhich the mind can rest.\u2014a. Iieaaeus 1\nPrime. I","height":"32440","width":"24000"}}
